  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2938160439" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2938160439" />
    <a title="David H." class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/18844431-david-h"><img alt="David H." src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1625448990p2/18844431.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2938160439?book_show_action=true">Feb 20, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="David H." class="user" itemprop="url" name="David H." href="/user/show/18844431-david-h">David H.</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Kindle Edition " href="/book/show/8785665-god-s-problem">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/18844431-david-h?shelf=nonfiction">nonfiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/18844431-david-h?shelf=audiobook">audiobook</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2938160439" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer13450246136296116815">I&apos;m not religious, but I&apos;ve been interested in Biblical archeology and history for a while (I even took a semester in college where I got to translate passages from the New Testament from Greek into English, which was fun). I&apos;d previously read Ehrman&apos;s <a href='https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/107273.Lost_Christianities_The_Battles_for_Scripture_and_the_Faiths_We_Never_Knew' title='Lost Christianities The Battles for Scripture and the Faiths We Never Knew by Bart D. Ehrman' rel='nofollow noopener'>Lost Christianities</a> and thought it was great, so I finally got around to another book by him.<br/><br/><i>God&apos;s Problem</i> is a lot more personal a book than I was expecting from the author, as it details some of the reasoning behind his loss of faith (he had pre</span>
  <span id="freeText13450246136296116815" style="display:none">I'm not religious, but I've been interested in Biblical archeology and history for a while (I even took a semester in college where I got to translate passages from the New Testament from Greek into English, which was fun). I'd previously read Ehrman's <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/107273.Lost_Christianities_The_Battles_for_Scripture_and_the_Faiths_We_Never_Knew" title="Lost Christianities The Battles for Scripture and the Faiths We Never Knew by Bart D. Ehrman" rel="nofollow noopener">Lost Christianities</a> and thought it was great, so I finally got around to another book by him.<br /><br /><i>God's Problem</i> is a lot more personal a book than I was expecting from the author, as it details some of the reasoning behind his loss of faith (he had previously been an evangelical Christian, but is now agnostic). As a whole, though, this book goes into the concept of theodicy (why does God allow evil?) and looks at the Bible (both Old and New Testaments) to see how the ancient Biblical writers tackled the question of suffering. He also mentions some of the modern answers to suffering (such as the free-will defense) and how they don't stack up either.<br /><br />Even though I knew some of the elements of which Ehrman discussed, I really appreciated the in-depth look at the text, especially for things I hadn't read too much analysis of before (such as the Book of Job and the Book of Revelations). I also came away with the feeling that the God as described in the Bible is completely heartless (using the Job example: killing Job's wife and children, and then at the end, "rewarding" him by giving him a new wife and new children... tough luck to the wife and kids that were killed for no reason but to test Job: The Ultimate Fridging).<br /><br />I really do like this kind of writing and analysis with regard to religion; I can't stand to read about Biblical archeology that presumptuously assumes textual accuracy and then tries to find evidence to back it up (I'm also not convinced that the Trojan War happened as told in the Iliad and the Odyssey, either, but good luck telling someone like Michael Wood that).</span>
  <a data-text-id="13450246136296116815" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


