<div id="review_2431561667" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2431561667" />
    <a title="Jamie" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/68583290-jamie"><img alt="Jamie" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1542573579p2/68583290.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2431561667?book_show_action=true">Jun 21, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Jamie" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Jamie" href="/user/show/68583290-jamie">Jamie</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/68583290-jamie?shelf=religion">religion</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2431561667" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer11915240523651852291">As Gertrude Stein said, “There ain&apos;t no answer. There ain&apos;t gonna be any answer. There never has been an answer. That&apos;s the answer.” And so, after examining the Bible’s explanations for suffering in this world, and finding them logically, morally, or intellectually insufficent (or indefensible), Ehrman is led back to the position of Ecclesiastes, which is that there is no explanation for suffering, there is no why. We are left with the inexplicable physical fact of brief lives accumulating pain </span>
  <span id="freeText11915240523651852291" style="display:none">As Gertrude Stein said, “There ain't no answer. There ain't gonna be any answer. There never has been an answer. That's the answer.” And so, after examining the Bible’s explanations for suffering in this world, and finding them logically, morally, or intellectually insufficent (or indefensible), Ehrman is led back to the position of Ecclesiastes, which is that there is no explanation for suffering, there is no why. We are left with the inexplicable physical fact of brief lives accumulating pain in larger or smaller amounts, and then we die. It is grim, but better an honest answer than a comforting lie. No one is going to rescue us from pain, and death is certain, but we can at least recognize the dignity in the lives of others and try our best to help where we can.</span>
  <a data-text-id="11915240523651852291" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
